The LSTM model was trained in the following way (Eq. 1). Let xt be a vector representing the t-th nucleotide in the input sequence. Only one element of xt is 1 and the others are 0. yt is a class indicator of nt defined by Eq. 1. The LSTM calculates zt for xt (Eq. 2). Softmax changes zt to a vector of values between 0 and 1 that sum to 1, and softmaxj is the j-th element of the output of the softmax (Eq. 3). The loss is the mean of the negative log-likelihood of the prediction (Eq. 4). The loss is used to update the hidden neurons in the hidden layer using the RMSProp algorithm [18]. When generating a sequence, the model takes a vector (0.25,0.25,0.25,0.25) as x1 and computes softmax(zt), a multinomial distribution of nucleotides. One character is sampled from the distribution and the vector of the character fed back to the model as x2. This process is repeated until it reaches the pre-determined length of the sequence.
